As a programming language, C provides a structured approach to writing code that can be executed by a computer. One of the fundamental concepts in C is the if/then statement, which allows you to execute a block of code based on a condition.

To write an if/then statement in C, you can use the following syntax:

if (condition) {
  // code to be executed if the condition is true
}

In this example, the if statement checks if the condition is true. If it is, the code inside the curly braces will be executed. If the condition is false, the code inside the curly braces will not be executed.

Here's an example of an if/then statement in C:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
  int age;
  printf("Enter your age: ");
  scanf("%d", &age);

  if (age >= 18) {
    printf("You are eligible to vote.\n");
  } else {
    printf("You are not eligible to vote.\n");
  }

  return 0;
}

In this example, the program prompts the user to enter their age. If the age is greater than or equal to 18, the program prints a message indicating that the user is eligible to vote. If the age is less than 18, the program prints a message indicating that the user is not eligible to vote.

